'''Audrey Ruth Churchill''' (née Briggs) (1920–2005) was a [[cryptanalyst]] at [[Bletchley Park]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>''Codebreakers – The inside story of Bletchley Park'', edited by [[F. H. Hinsley]] and Alan Stripp, [[Oxford University Press]]</ref> She graduated in Modern Languages from [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] and from 1942-1945, as an expert in German, worked at Bletchley Park as a member of the Z Watch, which translated the decrypted messages.<ref>[http://rollofhonour.bletchleypark.org.uk/search/record-detail/1122/ Bletchley Park Roll of Honour]</ref><ref>{{citation |pages=35–38 |title=In the Realms of Gold |author=Roland Oliver |publisher=Routledge |year=2013 |isbn=9781134571710}}</ref><ref name="BPRofH">[http://www.bletchleyparkresearch.co.uk/research-notes/women-codebreakers/  Bletchley Park Research : Women Codebreakers]</ref><ref>[http://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/women-were-key-code-breaking-bletchley-park-180954044/?no-ist Women Were Key to WWII Code-Breaking at Bletchley Park]</ref><ref>[http://www.newstatesman.com/2015/04/hard-nails ''The Bletchley Girls'' Tessa Dunlop, Hodder & Stoughton,]</ref>  She worked variously in Huts 4 and 5, Block A(N), and Naval Section NS I - German Cryptography.<ref name="BPRofH" />

In 1946 she married former [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]] Officer Major [[Oliver Churchill]] [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]] [[Military Cross|MC]] in [[Worcester Cathedral]] where her father [[GW Briggs]] was a [[Canon (priest)|Canon]], and her oldest son is [[Toby Churchill]].

