{{Infobox scientist | name = Ran Raz | native_name = {{lang-he|רָן רָז}} | native_name_lang = Hebrew | image = רן רז, 2011.jpg | birth_date = <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | nationality = | fields = {{Plainlist| *[[Computer science]] *[[Computational complexity theory]] }} | workplaces = {{Plainlist| *[[Princeton University]] *[[Weizmann Institute]] }} | alma_mater = [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] | thesis_title = Communication Complexity and Circuit Lower Bounds | thesis_year = 1992 | doctoral_advisor = {{Plainlist| *[[Avi Wigderson]] *Michael Ben-Or }} | doctoral_students = | known_for = | awards = [[Erdős Prize]] | website = {{URL|http://www.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il/~ranraz/}} }}
'''Ran Raz''' ({{lang-he|רָן רָז}}) is a [[computer scientist]] who works in the area of [[computational complexity theory]]. He was a professor in the faculty of mathematics and computer science at the [[Weizmann Institute]]. He is now a professor of computer science at [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cs.princeton.edu/news/raz-weinberg-deepen-faculty%E2%80%99s-leadership-critical-areas|title=Raz, Weinberg Deepen Faculty’s Leadership in Critical Areas {{!}} Computer Science Department at Princeton University|website=www.cs.princeton.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>
Ran Raz received his Ph.D. at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] in 1992 under [[Avi Wigderson]] and Michael Ben-Or.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|102217}}</ref>
Ran Raz is well known for his work on [[interactive proof system]]s. His two most-cited papers are {{harvtxt|Raz|1998}} on [[multi-prover interactive proof]]s and {{harvtxt|Raz|Safra|1997}} on [[probabilistically checkable proof]]s.<ref>Citations counts for {{harvtxt|Raz|1998}} as of 21 Feb 2009: Google Scholar: [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cites=10807229652058907596 313], ISI Web of Knowledge: 120, ACM Digital Library: [http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=284995.285007 57] + [http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=225058.225181 17], MathSciNet: [http://www.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1612640 53]. Citations counts for {{harvtxt|Raz|Safra|1997}} as of 21 Feb 2009: Google Scholar: [https://scholar.google.com/scholar?cites=16406540695585643205 314], ACM Digital Library: [http://portal.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=258533.258641 71], MathSciNet: [http://www.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1715654 59].</ref>
Ran Raz received the [[Erdős Prize]] in 2002. His work has been awarded in the top conferences in [[theoretical computer science]]. In 2004, he received the best paper award in ACM [[Symposium on Theory of Computing]] (STOC) for {{harvtxt|Raz|2004}},<ref>Proc. STOC 2004: "STOC 2004 Conference Awards", page x. [http://portal.acm.org/toc.cfm?id=1007352]. One of two award papers.</ref> and the best paper award in IEEE [[Conference on Computational Complexity]] (CCC) for {{harvtxt|Raz|Shpilka|2004}}.<ref>Proc. CCC 2004: "Awards", page x. [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/tocresult.jsp?isnumber=29139&isYear=2004].</ref> In 2008, the work {{harvtxt|Moshkovitz|Raz|2008}} received the best paper award in IEEE [[Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science]] (FOCS).<ref>Proc. FOCS 2008: "Foreword", page xii. [http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/tocresult.jsp?isnumber=4690924&isYear=2008].</ref>
